    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>The structural design method that DOES NOT take into account the safety factors on the design loads is</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "<p>working stress method.</p>"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "<p>load factor method.</p>"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "<p>ultimate load method.</p>"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "<p>limit state method.</p>"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The structural design method that does not take into account the safety factors on the design loads is described below:</p>\n\n<p>Option A: The working stress method.</p>\n\n<p>In the working stress method, the design is based on the elastic theory. It uses service loads and the structure is designed to remain within the elastic limits under these loads. Safety is implied by designing the structure to never exceed the service loads, but explicit safety factors, which are typical in methods such as the limit state method, are not explicitly accounted for in the calculation of design loads. Instead, safety factors are implicit in the allowable stresses used in the design process, leading it to be considered a more conservative approach.</p>\n\n<p>Let’s briefly look at the other options for context:</p>\n\n<p>Option B: The load factor method.</p>\n\n<p>This method explicitly includes safety factors by increasing the actual loads using load factors before designing the structure. It ensures that even if the loads exceed expected values, the structure will still be safe.</p>\n\n<p>Option C: The ultimate load method.</p>\n\n<p>Similar to the load factor method, this approach increases the working loads by a safety factor to obtain ultimate loads for which the structure must be designed.</p>\n\n<p>Option D: The limit state method.</p>\n\n<p>This method involves considering different limit states, including ultimate and serviceability limit states, with partial safety factors applied to both loads and material strengths.</p>\n\n<p>Therefore, the correct answer is:</p>\n\n<p><strong>Option A: The working stress method.</strong></p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2024,
    "yearKey": "gate-ce-2024-set-2",
    "difficulty": null
  },
